VL  - 15
IS  - 3
SP  - 717
EP  - 727
PY  - 1991
DA  - 1991/06/01/
SN  - 0378-4266
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0378-4266(91)90094-3
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0378426691900943
AB  - This paper compares active investment policies under three alternative models for estimating expected stock returns: the historical sample mean, a shrinkage or Bayesian estimator and a CAPM-based estimator. The out-of-sample performance of actively managed U.S. industry portfolios is analyzed for these three estimators over the period 1931 to 1987. It is found that the classical method, based on historical means and covariances, leads to the worst forecasts and out-of-sample performance, and is generally outperformed by shrinkage estimators. An active portfolio with expected returns based on the CAPM produced the best results among all actively managed portfolios; this strategy, as we show, closely matches a simple buy-and-hold the market rule.
